I mean, that's, I guess the question is that there's a lot of area that we don't know

29:42.280 --> 29:46.440
from when we go from one generation to the next, but what exactly is going on?

29:46.440 --> 29:49.640
But certainly if you look at multiple generations, you'll see the mark.

29:49.640 --> 29:53.200
It's whether it's staying there or whether it's just being reapplied.

29:53.200 --> 29:54.200
That's the question.

29:54.200 --> 29:55.200
Yeah.

29:55.200 --> 30:03.000
So I read one study where various histone variants had been tagged, and they did show

30:03.000 --> 30:08.760
that they were retained at least up to the first cell division after fertilization.

30:08.760 --> 30:15.840
But I think it is a compelling, you know, source of possibility that histone variants

30:15.840 --> 30:21.240
that are retained and not replaced by protomines could confer some information.

30:21.240 --> 30:27.320
It's important to keep in mind that the 10 to 17% that people have detected is enough

30:27.320 --> 30:29.640
to account for the entire coding genome.

30:29.640 --> 30:32.720
So I mean, there's enough information in there in theory.

30:32.720 --> 30:36.880
But it's also important to keep in mind, why don't we have these answers yet?

30:36.880 --> 30:42.200
And it's hard to study this because, you know, it's sort of like the wave particle

30:42.200 --> 30:45.280
duality in quantum physics.

30:45.280 --> 30:49.920
Once you look at that, once you take that sperm and egg that was going to become that

