46:54.080 --> 47:01.760
But as far as the role of epigenetics in cancer, meaning changes in the histones, changes in

47:01.760 --> 47:07.600
the DNA methylation, which in turn changed the chromatin structure and the whole relevance

47:07.600 --> 47:13.760
of changing the chromatin structure is the result is you change gene expression.

47:13.760 --> 47:18.200
So DNA, genetics information, is just information.

47:18.200 --> 47:22.080
DNA doesn't do anything other than carry information.

47:22.080 --> 47:28.880
It's the proteins and the RNAs that are copied from that information that are important,

47:28.880 --> 47:32.200
that will make you healthy, will make you sick.

47:32.200 --> 47:39.240
And so when the epigenetic information changes from what should be normally going on, that

47:39.240 --> 47:41.280
is what will cause disease.

47:41.280 --> 47:48.840
So there's clear evidence now that known tumor suppressors like P53, there are thousands

47:48.840 --> 47:55.440
and thousands of labs that study P53 and P53 mutation.

47:55.440 --> 48:03.280
There's clear evidence now that, so the mutation kills the function of the P53 protein, which

48:03.280 --> 48:06.680
normally stops cells dividing out of control.

48:06.680 --> 48:10.080
So now it's mutant, the cells will divide out of control.

48:10.080 --> 48:19.200
But there's evidence that the P53 gene product is inactivated just as frequently by epigenetic

48:19.200 --> 48:22.120
changes, not mutation.

48:22.120 --> 48:27.280
And there's growing evidence that that's the case with other important genes that are

48:27.280 --> 48:30.480
needed for protection from getting cancer.

48:30.480 --> 48:37.280
There's epigenetic changes that stop those genes from being expressed.

48:37.280 --> 48:38.880
And it's the harder thing to study.

48:38.880 --> 48:45.520
I mean, DNA sequencing is a lot easier than mapping epigenetic profiles.

48:45.520 --> 48:52.800
But I think there's a subset of cancer researchers that now believe that epigenetic changes could

48:52.800 --> 49:01.240
be the first changes that allow a subset of cells to divide more quickly.

49:01.240 --> 49:06.320
If you divide more quickly, you're more prone to DNA mutations.

49:06.320 --> 49:14.880
So some of us think that the epigenetic changes will lead to or provide a pool of cells that

49:14.880 --> 49:18.880
are selected for developing into cancer.

49:18.880 --> 49:24.880
And I think of evolution in a very similar way that I think these epigenetic changes

49:24.880 --> 49:33.920
that can happen quite rapidly as an environment changes allows us all to fit a certain niche.

49:33.920 --> 49:42.360
And then you have a population that is now more prone to a mutation that will stabilize

49:42.360 --> 49:46.200
that change in phenotype or behavior.

49:46.200 --> 49:53.200
So I think there's a lot of parallels between cancer and evolution.

49:53.200 --> 49:54.200
And also aging.

49:54.200 --> 49:57.320
I mean, our cells change as we age.

49:57.320 --> 50:02.160
And age is the largest risk factor for most cancers.

50:02.160 --> 50:08.600
So many of us are trying to understand the process of aging, to try and understand predisposition

50:08.600 --> 50:12.800
or delaying the onset of cancer.

50:12.800 --> 50:15.400
So yeah, it's a really hot area.

50:15.400 --> 50:22.960
And what's really exciting about epigenetic changes is that unlike genetic changes, so

50:22.960 --> 50:28.360
changes to your DNA, when your DNA changes, it's pretty much permanent.

50:28.360 --> 50:30.840
It cannot be reversed.

50:30.840 --> 50:38.120
The technologies are not available for us in the laboratory to reverse genetic changes,

50:38.120 --> 50:41.840
although that is likely to change pretty soon.

50:41.840 --> 50:50.960
But epigenetic changes, because their epigenetic information is put there by enzymes.

50:50.960 --> 50:53.760
So you're adding a chemical group by an enzyme.

50:53.760 --> 50:56.880
You're removing a chemical group by an enzyme.

50:56.880 --> 51:05.040
Our enzymes can be easily inhibited by designing small molecules or chemicals to block the

51:05.040 --> 51:07.160
active site of an enzyme.

51:07.160 --> 51:11.640
So there are many drugs that are out there and being developed by all the big pharma

51:11.640 --> 51:19.560
companies to block epigenetic enzymes in order to reverse these epigenetic changes.

51:19.560 --> 51:26.680
So the idea is you can now give these drugs to a cancer patient and now turn on the expression

51:26.680 --> 51:32.160
of the tumor suppressor gene to stop the cancer cells dividing out of control.

51:32.160 --> 51:40.080
So it's a huge area developing epigenetic drugs and also looking at the epigenetic signature

51:40.080 --> 51:49.120
to see if you can predict outcome of how bad the disease would be and predict which treatments

51:49.120 --> 51:55.480
would be more effective depending on not only the DNA sequence, but also the epigenetic

51:55.480 --> 51:57.800
information.

